The White House Press Secretary, Josh Earnest, held a press briefing on June 30, 2014. Earnest discussed a range of topics including the Supreme Court ruling on the Hobby Lobby case, the crisis of unaccompanied minors at the border, the situation in Iraq, the nomination of Bob McDonald as Secretary of Veterans Affairs, and the ongoing tensions with Russia. Earnest emphasized the need for Congress to take action to address the concerns raised by the Supreme Court ruling on the Hobby Lobby case, particularly in ensuring that women still have access to vital health services. He also highlighted the importance of addressing the humanitarian crisis of unaccompanied minors at the border and the need for comprehensive immigration reform. Additionally, Earnest stressed the need for Iraq's political leaders to pursue an inclusive governing agenda in order to confront the threat posed by ISIL and bring stability to the country. He expressed confidence in Bob McDonald's ability to lead the Department of Veterans Affairs, citing his extensive management experience and commitment to serving military families. Finally, Earnest reiterated the administration's stance on Russia's actions in Ukraine, calling for de-escalation of the conflict and warning of additional economic costs if Russia does not take concrete actions to address the situation.